06695nam a22009015i 9781782382812DE-B159720221107062033.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221107t20142014nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2013023291  a97817823828127 a10.1515/97817823828122doi  a(DE-B1597)636472  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aP96.H55bS55 2014 4aP96.H55b.S55 2014eb 7aSOC0520002bisacsh  aAP 13800qBVB2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/6889:00aSilence, Screen, and Spectacle :bRethinking Social Memory in the Age of Information /ced. by Lindsey A. Freeman, Benjamin Nienass, Rachel Daniell. 1aNew York; aOxford : bBerghahn Books, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (260 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aRemapping Cultural History ;v1400tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Rethinking Social Memory in the Age of Information -- tPart I Spectacular Memory: Memory and Appearance in the Age of Information -- tChapter 1 Haunted by the Spectre of Communism: Spectacle and Silence in Hungary’s House of Terror -- tChapter 2 Making Visible: Reflexive Narratives at the Manzanar U.S. National Historic Site -- tChapter 3 The Everyday as Spectacle: Archival Imagery and the Work of Reconciliation in Canada -- tPart II Screening Absence: New Technology, Affect, and Memory -- tChapter 4 Viral Affiliations: Facebook, Queer Kinship, and the Memory of the Disappeared in Contemporary Argentina -- tChapter 5 Learning by Heart: Humming, Singing, Memorizing in Israeli Memorial Videos -- tChapter 6 Arcade Mode: Remembering, Revisiting, and Replaying the American Video Arcade -- tPart III Silence and Memory: Erasures, Storytelling, and Kitsch -- tChapter 7 Remembering Forgetting: A Monument to Erasure at the University of North Carolina -- tChapter 8 The Power of Conflicting Memories in European Transnational Social Movements -- tChapter 9 Memories of Jews and the Holocaust in Post-Communist Eastern Europe: The Case of Poland -- tChapter 10 1989 as Collective Memory “Refolution” East-Central Europe Confronts Memorial Silence -- tConclusion: Comments on Silence, Screen, and Spectacle -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn an age of information and new media the relationships between remembering and forgetting have changed. This volume addresses the tension between loud and often spectacular histories and those forgotten pasts we strain to hear. Employing social and cultural analysis, the essays within examine mnemonic technologies both new and old, and cover subjects as diverse as U.S. internment camps for Japanese Americans in WWII, the Canadian Indian Residential School system, Israeli memorial videos, and the desaparecidos in Argentina. Through these cases, the contributors argue for a re-interpretation of Guy Debord’s notion of the spectacle as a conceptual apparatus through which to examine the contemporary landscape of social memory, arguing that the concept of spectacle might be developed in an age seen as dissatisfied with the present, nervous about the future, and obsessed with the past. Perhaps now “spectacle” can be thought of not as a tool of distraction employed solely by hegemonic powers, but instead as a device used to answer Walter Benjamin’s plea to “explode the continuum of history” and bring our attention to now-time.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aCollective memory. 0aHispanic American mass mediaxTechnological innovationsxSocial aspects. 0aInformation technologyxSocial aspects. 0aMass media and history. 0aMass mediaxTechnological innovationsxSocial aspects. 0aMemorialization. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Media Studies.2bisacsh1 aAngel, Naomi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc